\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Machine Learning and Application in Multi-Criteria Decision Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
La Minh Hoang
\end_layout

\begin_layout Right Address
University of Zielona Gora
\end_layout

\begin_layout Right Address
Faculty of Mathematics, Computer Science and Econometrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Right Address
Poland
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multi-criteria Decision Analysis (MCDA) which also can be call as "Multiple
 Criteria Decision-Making" or "Multi-criteria Decision Aiding'' in English
 or "Analyse Multicritère" in French is an exciting field which has seen
 many achievements including increasing number of research papers, books,
 and theoretical over the years since the 60s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pugnaire1992multicriteria,roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For many decision makers, MCDA is an excellent tool in getting comprehensive
 insight information when solving a decision problem especially when there
 are many different factors are taken into account 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pugnaire1992multicriteria,roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this thesis, we will show to the readers how to incorporate Machine Learning
 in MCDA.
 Thus, to prove the feasibility of this incorporation; first, we will point
 out some difficulties which MCDA has when dealing with complicated decision
 problems, especially problems that repeat many times.
 Then we will see what advantages of Machine Learning can offer to solve
 these difficulties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make more sense to the readers, the contents of this thesis will be structure
d as follow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Multi-criteria-Decision-Analysis"

\end_inset

, readers will be greeted with basic concepts of MCDA and what we should
 expect from MCDA when using it to solve a decision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:The-Method-of"

\end_inset

, we will show the concept of Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP) which is
 an MCDA method to derive priority or ratio scales from paired comparisons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Soft-Computing-with"

\end_inset

, we will focus on the detail of Machine Learning, especially Artificial
 Neural Network (ANN) and Adaptive Neuro - Fuzzy Inference System (ANFIS).
 ANN and ANFIS are two methods of Machine Learning which are the potential
 candidates for incorporating with MCDA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Case-Studies"

\end_inset

, we will design a system in which Machine Learning will play a major role
 in the MCDA process.
 With this system are two study cases which will show how effective Machine
 Learning can be in improving the decision making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we will conclude the thesis with some conclusions which summarise
 the points of this thesis.
 Because the study for this thesis still in the early stage, we will also
 propose some suggestions for future improvements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Multi-criteria Decision Analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Multi-criteria-Decision-Analysis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To begin this chapter, we will examine the foundation theory of MCDA which
 is the Decision Theory in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-foundation-of"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we will have a look at the structure of a typical decision-making
 process and how it operates in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Structure-of-decision-making"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-process-of"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we will explain the reasons why people use MCDA for aiding the decision
 making process in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Why-people-use"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:From-Monocriteria-to"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After having a brief description of Decision Theory, decision-making process
 and why we need MCDA, we will delve deep into the philosophy and paradigms
 of MCDA in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Basic-concept-mcda"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will also list some interest MCDA methods in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:MCDA-Methods"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The foundation of MCDA: Decision Theory
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-foundation-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision Theory, in general, is simply a theory about making decisions.
 However, it is not an easy task to precisely define what Decision Theory
 is.
 It is because Decision Theory is truly an interdisciplinary subject which
 is pursued by researchers from many disciplines such as economists, statisticia
ns, psychologist, political and social scientists or philosophers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wiki:decision_theory"

\end_inset

.
 Each discipline has its way of studying and theorising Decision Theory,
 for example, a psychologist might want to investigate the behaviour of
 people when they are making decisions, an economist is likely to study
 the payoffs of each decision or a political scientist will try to find
 the optimal voting rule by studying Decision Theory.
 However, if we abstract Decision Theory from all disciplines, we can see
 that Decision Theory is all about theorising human activities in situations
 where there are a goal and options to choose between in order to reach
 that goal, in other words, decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can generalise the Decision Theory into two definitions: one is broad,
 and the other one is narrow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lectureUZ"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Broad definition
\series default
: Decision Theory is the set of all possible disciplines connected with
 making decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Narrow definition
\series default
: Decision Theory is the set of theoretical consideration of what is a decision,
 what is decision situation, what are elements of a decision situation,
 what is right or optimal decision and how to make a right or optimal decision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also important to know that Decision Theory has two main branches:
 Normative Decision Theory and Descriptive Decision Theory.
 The brief definitions of those two branches can be given as follow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Normative Decision Theory
\series default
 concerns about constructing rules and methods of making decisions that
 in the context of an ideal decision maker (i.e.
 decision maker with perfect information) can identify the best decision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Descriptive Decision Theory
\series default
 interests in the psychological or behavioural aspect of the decision maker
 (i.e.
 how do people in real situations make their decisions).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, readers should notice the direction of the thesis in term of which
 branch of Decision Theory we will go from here.
 Because the goal of this study is to introduce a new approach, in this
 case, Machine Learning techniques, to enhance the process of making a decision;
 therefore, the majority of this study will be in the context of Normative
 Decision Theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Structure-of-decision-making"

\end_inset

 we will examine the structure of a typical decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Structure of a decision-making process
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Structure-of-decision-making"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Typically, a decision-making process comprises of these elements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lectureUZ"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Decision
\series default
 makers: The decision makers themselves, they are the ones who are responsible
 for the consequences of their decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Goal
\series default
: The desired state of our decision problem, usually it is what we want
 to achieve after solving the decision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Initial
\series default
 state: The beginning state of our decision problem i.e.
 all the measurements, parameters, conditions or factors we have before
 starting the decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Decisions
\series default
: The options or alternative courses of action which are the possibilities
 of realising our goal or desired state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Criterion
\series default
: A measurement or a standard which allows comparing between different options
 or alternatives.
 The criterion can be profit, cost, time, effort, property, measurable index,
 measurable attribute or measurable characteristic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Constraints
\series default
: Limitations stated by the decision problem.
 It can also be used to decide the polarity of a criterion, i.e.
 to decide if a criterion is a positive criterion or negative criterion.
 For example, if a decision problem has time constraint then evaluation
 from criteria related to time such as time to manufacture, time to delivery,
 response time or time to travel should be as small as possible.
 In other words, those criteria are negative criteria, i.e.
 the smaller the value, the better the evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Consequences
\series default
: Outcomes or results we get after realising the goal with the option or
 alternative we have chosen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Uncertainty
\series default
: The set of all consequences that are outside the set of expected consequences
 of the goal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Preferences
\series default
: The view of each decision maker which determines the importance of each
 criterion.
 For example, in a decision problem where the time and cost are criteria,
 a decision maker may think time is the most important criterion while the
 other decision maker may think the opposite, cost is the most important
 criterion.
 Therefore, an alternative with high evaluation from time criterion may
 be appealing to decision makers who value time criterion while at the same
 time being ignored by decision makers who value cost criterion.
 This element is the most important one in a decision situation because
 it directly affects the performance of an alternative in different decision
 maker view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The process of making a decision
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-process-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between elements in a decision-making process is presented
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Components-of-a"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lectureUZ"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename img/Components of a decision-making process.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Components-of-a"

\end_inset

Elements of a decision-making process
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Components-of-a"

\end_inset

, all the elements of decision-making process are drawn as members of an
 analysis process.
 As we can see, the process starts first by formulating the Initial State
 of the decision problem, so then we can find the Constraints of the decision
 problem, determine the Criteria and construct the Alternatives.
 Then this information is given to Decision Makers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After formulating the information from the Initial State, each Decision
 Maker with his or her Preferences takes part in an Evaluating Process along
 with the given Alternatives, Criteria and Constraints.
 During the Evaluating Process, one alternative or combination of alternatives
 which is considered the best comparing to other alternatives is chosen
 to realise the goal of the decision situation.
 Finally, after realising the goal using the selected alternative, we get
 the outcomes from the realisation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These outcomes belong to the Uncertainty set because no matter how careful
 the Evaluating Process is executed by Decision Makers, there are always
 some uncontrollable and unforeseeable factors that could affect the outcomes.
 In other words, we can make a good decision by thorough deliberation in
 the process of Evaluating Process and take into account all possible informatio
n from Initial State, but because of the Uncertainty, we cannot know for
 sure if that decision is the right decision or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Why-people-use"

\end_inset

, we will present to the readers the concept of Decision Analysis and why
 it is important to have Decision Analysis in every decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The necessary of Decision Analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Why-people-use"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-foundation-of"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Structure-of-decision-making"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-process-of"

\end_inset

, we have known that in a decision-making process, decision makers have
 the responsibility to choose the right decision in order to realise the
 goal in that particular situation.
 However, there are many factors with hidden information in a decision-making
 process that can hide the true value of each decision thus affect the judgement
 of the decision maker.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, when choosing suppliers for providing materials to build a
 particular product.
 If we do not spend the time to research the past performance of each supplier,
 we will never know the true value of each supplier in term of providing
 the needed materials.
 Thus our judgment for choosing the suppliers will not be certain.
 To overcome this difficulty of uncertain judgment, a decision maker will
 need to practice Decision Analysis in a decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision Analysis or Decision Aiding (DA) can be defined as follows 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

: It is the activity of using explicit and formalised models to help obtain
 elements of responses to the questions posed by a stakeholder in a decision
 process.
 In other words, it is the process of getting more information from the
 context of the decision-making process to clarify various components inside
 a decision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the above definition, DA's purpose is to establish the decision-making
 process with working hypotheses, formulations of propositions (satisfying
 solutions or possible compromises) which clears out the uncertainty in
 the decision maker's judgement 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

 .
 In such case, DA can contribute to the follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Analysing the context of the decision-making process by various means such
 as identifying the actors, the possibilities of action, their consequences,
 or the stakes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Organising and structuring how the decision-making process should proceed
 to improve the consistency among the values underlying the goal and the
 final decision that realise that goal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Getting the actors (such as the decision maker and the expert who is providing
 the information related to the decision) to cooperate by proposing a way
 to improve mutual understanding and a framework that comfortable to debate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Elaborating recommendations by using the models or procedures which are
 formulated within the context of a working hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aiding in the final decision legitimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:From-Monocriteria-to"

\end_inset

, we will present to readers the notions of Mono-criteria and Multi-criteria,
 thus the reason why MCDA is the prefer tool for many decision makers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From Mono-criteria to Multi-criteria
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:From-Monocriteria-to"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a decision-making process, a decision maker has two approaches to evaluate
 the options.
 They are Mono-criteria and Multi-criteria.
 To simply put, Mono-criteria is when the decision maker only uses one criterion
 for determining the value of each option of the decision problem.
 Multi-criteria, on the other hand, evaluate each option on many different
 criteria that associating with various aspects of the decision problem.
 Readers can find more information about criterion in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Basic-concept-mcda"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a decision maker is dealing with a DA process, it is very rare for
 the decision maker to have in mind only one single clear criterion (Mono-criter
ia).
 In a multi-actor environment, it is even more unlikely for that single
 criterion to satisfy the point of view of every actor in the decision-making
 process because each actor plays a different role in that process which
 gives different preference to the actor own objectives and value system
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any case, it is essential to consider every point of view dealing with
 many perspectives of a decision-making process, for example, the financial
 status, the current human resources, the affected ecosystem, security or
 quality of services.
 By regarding each related point of view individually, independently from
 the others, it is likely to arrive at a clear decision that meets all actors'
 preferences and requirements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, it is typical to associating a particular criterion to each related
 point of view (Multi-criteria).
 For each associated criterion, it will be used to evaluate any potential
 action on an appropriate qualitative or quantitative scale 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we can see, in many decision-making contexts, using Mono-criteria approach
 might overlook certain aspects of the decision problem, thus affecting
 the judgement of the decision maker.
 Using Multi-criteria approach in such cases will help the decision maker
 to avoid the before-mentioned danger of neglecting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Basic-concept-mcda"

\end_inset

, we will explore the three basic concepts of MCDA which will give us a
 throughout view of the structure of a Decision Analysis process that connects
 with Multi-criteria to help the decision maker in solving his or her decision
 problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Basic Concepts of MCDA
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Basic-concept-mcda"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following concepts have a fundamental role in the process of analysing
 and structuring the decision-making process with MCDA:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Alternatives
\series default
 which defines the options that the decision maker has to decide to choose
 one as the way to realise the goal in a decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Criterion or Criteria
\series default
 which acts as a tool to evaluate and compare between alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following subsections will present to the readers the definitions of
 each concept so the readers can generalise what an MCDA process is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Alternatives
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Alternatives"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a decision-making process, to make a decision, the decision maker have
 to choose an action with the purpose of realising the goal of the decision
 problem by using the chosen action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action in this sense can be defined as a potential action which constitutes
 to the object of the decision or one of the objectives of the decision
 analysis process.
 However, not all action can be qualified as a potential action.
 The action must be considered to be possible to implement it or justifies
 some interests within the decision analysis process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the definition of potential action, the concept of alternative is often
 modelled in two ways 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Mutual
\series default
 
\series bold
exclusive
\series default
: Two distinct potential actions must not be conjointly put into realising
 the goal of the decision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Non-mutual
\series default
 
\series bold
exclusive
\series default
: Various potential actions can conjointly be put together to realise the
 goal of the decision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many authors believed that potential actions should be mutual exclusive,
 but it is not always the case 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
 In many real world decision analysis contexts, it is appropriate to combine
 several potential actions into realising the goal of the decision problem
 rather than using only one potential action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, for any decision analysis process, there is always a set of
 more than two potential actions or alternatives, and this set is not fixed
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
 During the decision analysis process, this set can evolve i.e.
 adding more potential actions as a result of investigating every aspect
 of the decision problem.
 For example, the investigation can help gain more knowledge about the goal,
 constraints, the preferences of the stakeholders, the possible outcomes
 of the actions, and other aspects of the decision problem.
 Thus, this new knowledge could open new boundary that helps to identify
 other actions as potential action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the set of all potential actions or alternatives in a decision-making
 process, we will use 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to denote it.
 To designate a potential action or alternative, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 When the number of actions is finite 
\begin_inset Formula $(|A|=m)$
\end_inset

 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{m}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each potential action, when we can model the action by referring to
 some variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x1,x2,x3,...$
\end_inset

 we can write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=(x_{1},x_{2},...)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use the above notions to describe the definition of Criterion in
 the next 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Criterion-and-Family"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Criterion and Family of Criteria
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Criterion-and-Family"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The readers should recall from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:From-Monocriteria-to"

\end_inset

 that a criterion is used as a tool to determine the value of an alternative.
 By using the notion of potential action 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Alternatives"

\end_inset

, we can denote a criterion as a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 which evaluates a potential action or alternative; this function then outputs
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $performance$
\end_inset

 value associating with the input potential action.
 We will denote this evaluation as 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)$
\end_inset

 is a real number.
 However, it is necessary to define a set 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{g}$
\end_inset

 of all possible evaluations that the criterion g can produce.
 This set 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{g}$
\end_inset

 should also follow a scale system to be accepted by all stakeholders in
 an MCDA process
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X_{g}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\begin_inset Formula $degree$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $score$
\end_inset

 of the scale.
 We can use any number, verbal statement or pictogram to designate a degree.
 During the comparison between two alternatives, we compare the two degrees
 which represent the respective performances of the two alternatives according
 to criterion 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many types of scales which readers should notice; the following
 two scales are the most typical 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Purely ordinal scale or qualitative scale
\series default
: The gap between two degrees does not have a clear meaning i.e.
 we only know the ranking of the degrees, we do not know how close or far
 from one degree to another.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Quantitative scale
\series default
: The degrees in this scale are defined by a clear quantity in a way that
 it gives meanings i.e.
 we can count the differences between two different degrees.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
MCDA Methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:MCDA-Methods"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision Makers can use different methods to analyse the alternatives and
 find the best alternative or the group of best alternatives, some of these
 methods do not require criteria to have weights, while others do require
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lectureUZ"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the following methods do not use weights:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Pareto
\series default
 
\series bold
Rule
\series default
: We will choose from the given alternatives the set of alternatives which
 are non-dominated by any other alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Conjunctive
\series default
 
\series bold
Method
\series default
: We will define levels of satisfaction for all criteria then for each criterion
 we find the set of alternatives which satisfies it.
 After getting all the sets of satisfying alternatives for each criterion,
 we will intersect all those sets and the resulting set from the intersecting
 will be our chosen set of alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Disjunctive Method
\series default
: Similar to Conjunctive Method but we will choose alternatives which are
 good for at least one criterion.
 In other words, instead of intersecting all the sets of satisfying alternatives
 for each criterion, we find the union of all those sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, these following examples are methods which do require
 Criteria to have weights:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Lexicographic Method
\series default
: We will order the criteria from the most important to the less important.
 The ordering will be based on the weights of the criteria.
 Then, we will choose alternatives which are the best with respect to the
 first ranking criterion base on the evaluation of the Decision Table.
 If there is only one such alternative, then we will stop the process.
 If there are more such alternatives (more than two), we will continue to
 choose from these alternatives the ones which are the best with respect
 to the second ranking criterion.
 We will continue the process unless we reach the last criterion in the
 ordering or there is only one alternative left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Weighted Average Method
\series default
: We will calculate the weighted average for each alternative by multiplying
 the Scaled Decision Table with Criteria weights.
 By comparing the scores and select the biggest one, we will have our best
 alternative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above methods are just simple methods, however, there are other methods
 that are complicated and can be used in complex decision problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wiki:ahp2017"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Analytic hierarchy process (AHP)
\series default
: a method to derive priority or ratio scales from paired comparisons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
ELECTRE
\series default
: this method is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

outranking method
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of decision making which is applied to three main problems: choosing, ranking,
 and sorting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
PROMETHEE
\series default
: is also another 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

outranking method
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but it can be used both in normative approach and descriptive approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the next 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:The-Method-of"

\end_inset

, we will present to the readers a comprehensive description of AHP method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Method of Analytic Hierarchy Process
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:The-Method-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we will get into the details of Analytic Hierarchy Process
 (AHP) by answering questions such as: What is AHP? Who created it? Which
 kind of decision problem can we apply AHP?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After getting the general ideas about AHP, we will delve deep into the methodolo
gy and core elements of AHP such as: What is the Pair-wise comparison? How
 to make a Comparison Matrix? How to calculate priority vector? How to use
 Consistency Index and Consistency Ration to verify the comparisons?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explaining AHP using only its definitions can be tough at some points.
 Therefore we will use an example to explain each aspect of AHP.
 It is easier to understand the concept of AHP that way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Brief History of Analytic Hierarchy Process 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Brief-Introduction-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP) is created by Professor Thomas L.
 Saaty as a Multi-Criteria decision-making method.
 This method is described in the book “Mathematical Principles of Decision
 Making” or “Principia Mathematica Decernendi” which Prof.
 Saaty wrote in the 70s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "web:goepel_ahp"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, Analytic Hierarchy Process is a method to derive priority or
 ratio scales (we will use the word “priority” and “ratio” interchangeably)
 from paired comparisons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saaty2008decision"

\end_inset

.
 The input of AHP method is obtained from actual measurements such as price,
 weight, area, or from subjective opinion such as satisfaction feelings
 or preference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "teknomoAHPtutorial"

\end_inset

.
 To derive the ratio scales, we need to solve the principal Eigenvectors
 problem and then to verify the scales we will use Consistency Index which
 is calculated from Eigenvalue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve a decision problem by using AHP, we need to decompose the decision
 problem into the following steps 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Saaty:1980ahp"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Define the problem and determine the kind of knowledge sought – in other
 words, we set the goal of the decision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Structure the hierarchy of the decision problem.
 The goal of the decision problem will be on the top level of the hierarchy.
 Then you will put the objectives or criteria (and sub-criteria) in the
 intermediate levels.
 Finally, at the lowest level will be the set of alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Construct a set of pairwise comparison matrices.
 In which, each element in an upper level is compared to the elements in
 the level immediately below to it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the priorities from the comparison matrices in each level of the
 hierarchy until the last priorities of the alternatives in the lowest level
 of our hierarchy are obtained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After obtaining priorities for the alternatives in the decision problem,
 we should calculate the Consistency Index and Consistency Ratio to see
 if our comparisons are logical and consistent.
 If not, we have to revise our comparisons to get a more consistent set
 of priorities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the priorities are consistent, we can use them to evaluate our alternatives
 and select the optimal alternative for our decision problem, i.e.
 the alternative with the highest priority.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because AHP allows small inconsistency in making comparison 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "teknomoAHPtutorial"

\end_inset

, we can use AHP to solve various decision problems, from making simple
 and straightforward decisions to complex and high-stakes problems in which
 human perceptions and judgements are required 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wiki:ahp2017"

\end_inset

, for example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Choice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Ranking
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Quality management
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Conflict resolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One fascinating example of AHP application is suspect identification by
 witnesses in criminal cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mu2013new"

\end_inset

.
 Usually, candidates for identification are shown altogether or sequential,
 but in the AHP case, they are shown in pairs.
 Comparisons between pairs are then made by the witnesses.
 Studies have shown that by using AHP method, the reliability of identification
 has been increased from 55% to 83% and the false identification rate has
 been reduced from 20% to 17% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mu2013new"

\end_inset

.
 Also, the consistency index produced by AHP method is a good indicator
 for telling if the statements made by witnesses are consistent or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Pair-wise comparison
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Pair-wise-comparison"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most fundamental element of AHP method is the Pair-wise comparison.
 In short, it is like asking between two objects, which one do you prefer
 and how much do you prefer it to the other object.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have two cars made by two different manufacturers, one is from
 Renault, and the other is from Toyota.
 To make a pair-wise comparison between these two cars, we will use a relative
 scale in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Relative-scale-between"

\end_inset

 to measure how much we prefer a car compare to the other 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saaty2008decision"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename img/Relative scale between two car manufacturers.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Relative-scale-between"

\end_inset

Relative scale between two car manufacturers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above relative scale, if we prefer the Toyota car than the Renault
 car, we choose a number which is a preference value between one and nine
 on the left side of the scale.
 If we prefer the Renault car otherwise, we choose a number on the right
 side of the scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preference values or judgement values are used to describe how strong
 our preference is over a car.
 The following 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:Judgement-table"

\end_inset

 explains the judgement values 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saaty2008decision"

\end_inset


\end_layout

