\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Please be noticed that all values in the comparison matrix must be positive,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Priority-Vector"

\end_inset

, we will use this comparison matrix to calculate the eigenvalues and eigenvecto
rs to calculate the final priorities or Priority Vector of our alternatives
 which are the three car models in Darek example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Priority Vector
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Priority-Vector"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the complete comparison matrix in the previous section, we can now
 find the priority vector for our alternatives.
 However, first, we need to calculate the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of
 the matrix because the priority vector is the normalised principal Eigenvector
 of the matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually, eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a matrix are calculated by using
 computer programs such as MATLAB or Maxima due to the increasing complexity
 in calculation when the size of the matrix is getting bigger.
 However, for small matrices with size 
\begin_inset Formula $n\leq3$
\end_inset

 like the one in our example, it is possible to use an approximation method
 to approximate the normalised principal Eigenvector with low error rate
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "teknomoAHPtutorial"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approximation method is very easy to use.
 All we need to do is just to normalise each column in the comparison matrix.
 For example, we got 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:Complete-comparison-matrix"

\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Comparison-Matrix"

\end_inset

, then we sum each column of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:Complete-comparison-matrix"

\end_inset

 to get the following 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:Comparison-matrix-summed"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Comparison-matrix-summed"

\end_inset

Comparison matrix summed by column
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="5" columns="4">
<features booktabs="true" tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Toyota
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Renault
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ford
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Toyota
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\text{1}}{5}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Renault
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
5
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
7
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ford
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{7}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sum
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
9
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{47}{35}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{25}{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get the approximation of the normalised principal Eigenvector we just
 need to average the matrix across the rows as follow:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v=\frac{1}{3}\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{9}+\frac{7}{47}+\frac{1}{25}\\
\frac{5}{9}+\frac{35}{47}+\frac{21}{25}\\
\frac{1}{3}+\frac{5}{47}+\frac{3}{25}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}0.1000\\
0.7134\\
0.1866
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq:eigenv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have got the priority vector or the approximation of the normalised
 principal Eigenvector of the comparison matrix.
 Since the sum of all elements in the priority vector is 1, it tells us
 the relative weights of all alternatives we have compared.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By having the priority vector, we can say the weight or the priority of
 each car model in our example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Toyota car is 10%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Renault car is 71.34%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Ford car is 18.66%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to these weights, the Renault car has the highest priority (71.34%)
 among the three car models.
 Therefore, Darek can easily choose the Renault car as his new car.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, we need to verify if the comparisons made by Darek is consistent
 or not.
 To do this, we need to calculate the Principal Eigenvalue.
 It can be obtained in our approximation by the summation of products between
 each element of the priority vector and the sum of columns of the comparison
 matrix 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "teknomoAHPtutorial"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{max}=9*(0.1)+\frac{47}{35}*(0.7134)+\frac{25}{3}*(0.1866)=3.4129\label{eq:eigen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this Principal Eigenvalue, we can verify the consistency of our pair-wise
 comparisons by calculating the Consistency Index and Consistency Ratio
 which will be shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Consistency-Index-and"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Consistency Index and Consistency Ratio
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Consistency-Index-and"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consistency of pair-wise comparison is closely related to the transitive
 property 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "teknomoAHPtutorial"

\end_inset

.
 Which means for a person who prefers A than B or 
\begin_inset Formula $A\succ B$
\end_inset

 and he also prefers B than C or 
\begin_inset Formula $B\succ C$
\end_inset

 then according to transitive property, this person should prefer A than
 C or 
\begin_inset Formula $A\succ C$
\end_inset

.
 If for any reason, this particular person does not prefer A than C, but
 he prefers C than A or 
\begin_inset Formula $C\succ A$
\end_inset

, then we can say that his comparisons over A, B, and C are inconsistent
 with each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let’s check this consistency in our example in
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Comparison-Matrix"

\end_inset

.
 Based on the three comparisons in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Darek's-pair-wise-comparisons"

\end_inset

, we can see that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Darek prefers the Renault car more than the Ford car or 
\begin_inset Formula $Renault\succ Ford$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Darek prefers the Ford car more than the Toyota car or 
\begin_inset Formula $Ford\succ Toyota$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Darek prefers the Renault car more than the Toyota car or 
\begin_inset Formula $Renault\succ Toyota$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, the comparisons made by Darek appear to be consistent: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Renault\succ Ford\land Ford\succ Toyota\Longrightarrow Renault\succ Toyota\label{eq:transitivity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
(satisfies the transitive property)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If Darek had made the last comparison as follow: 
\begin_inset Formula $Toyota\succ Renault$
\end_inset

, then this comparison will be inconsistent with other comparisons thus
 making Darek judgement in choosing new car inconsistent and not reliable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, there is a problem with this check.
 This check does not take into account of how much Darek prefer each car.
 Therefore, we cannot know if the values in the comparison matrix are consistent
 with each other or not.
 This fact can make the whole hierarchy of AHP (especially multi-level hierarchy
) becomes inconsistent because we have to make a pair-wise comparison in
 each level of the hierarchy and the immediately lower level will use the
 priority vector produced by pair-wise comparison of the base level to calculate
 its global weights 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saaty2008decision"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to Prof.
 Saaty, for a consistent comparison matrix to be consistent, the largest
 Eigenvalue should be equal to the size of the comparison matrix, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{max}=n$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "saaty2008decision"

\end_inset

.
 Then, to know how many degrees of consistent a comparison matrix is, Prof.
 Saaty gave us a measurement of consistency, the Consistency Index or CI.
 To calculate this index, we use the following formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CI=\frac{\lambda_{max}-n}{n-1}\label{eq:cii}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, applying into our example which has 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{max}=3.4129$
\end_inset

 and the size of the comparison matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

; we have the consistency index as follow: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CI=\frac{\lambda_{max}-n}{n-1}=\frac{3.4129-3}{2}=0.20645\label{eq:ci}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, how can we use this index to determine the consistency of our comparison?
 Once again, according to Prof.
 Saaty, by comparing it with the appropriate one we can know how many degrees
 of consistent our comparison matrix is.
 The proper consistency index is called Random Consistency Index or RI 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Saaty:1980ahp"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prof.
 Saaty had pre-calculated the Random Consistency Index for comparison matrix
 using a 1-9 scale based on a sample size of 500 random generated reciprocal
 matrices in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:Pre-calculated-Random-Consistenc"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Saaty:1980ahp"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:Pre-calculated-Random-Consistenc"

\end_inset

Pre-calculated Random Consistency Index
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
